          <h3>Binary Trees</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 1: What is a Binary Tree?

            A **binary tree** is a hierarchical data structure where:

            - Each node has **at most two children**
            - These children are called:
              - **Left child**
              - **Right child**

            ####N_{children} \leq 2####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Root]-->B[Left];
              A-->C[Right];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 2: Basic Terminology

            Important terms:

            - **Root**: Top node
            - **Leaf**: Node with no children
            - **Parent / Child**
            - **Subtree**

            ####Leaf = node\ with\ 0\ children####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Root]-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D[Leaf];
              B-->E[Leaf];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 3: Structure of a Node

            Each node typically contains:

            - A **value**
            - A reference to:
              - **left child**
              - **right child**

            ####Node = (value, left, right)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Node]-->B[Left pointer];
              A-->C[Right pointer];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 4: Types of Binary Trees

            Common types:

            - **Full Binary Tree**: Every node has 0 or 2 children
            - **Complete Binary Tree**: Filled left to right
            - **Perfect Binary Tree**: All levels fully filled

            ####Nodes_{perfect} = 2^h - 1####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
              C-->F;
              C-->G;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 5: Height of a Binary Tree

            - Height = longest path from root to leaf

            ####h = max(depth\ of\ leaves)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              B-->C;
              C-->D;
              D-->E;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 6: Tree Traversals

            Ways to visit nodes:

            - **Inorder** (Left, Root, Right)
            - **Preorder** (Root, Left, Right)
            - **Postorder** (Left, Right, Root)

            ####Traversal = visiting\ all\ nodes####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 7: Inorder Traversal Example

            Steps:

            1. Visit left subtree
            2. Visit root
            3. Visit right subtree

            ####Inorder: L \rightarrow Root \rightarrow R####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              A-->C;
              B-->D;
              B-->E;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 8: Binary Tree vs Binary Search Tree

            Binary Tree:
            - No ordering rules

            Binary Search Tree (BST):
            - Left < Root < Right

            ####Left < Root < Right####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[10]-->B[5];
              A-->C[15];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 9: Applications of Binary Trees

            Used in:

            - Expression parsing
            - File systems
            - Databases
            - AI (decision trees)

            ####Tree \rightarrow hierarchical\ data####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Decision]-->B[Yes];
              A-->C[No];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 10: Advantages and Limitations

            Advantages:
            - Efficient searching (in BST)
            - Natural hierarchy

            Limitations:
            - Can become unbalanced
            - Worst-case operations: O(n)

            ####Best = O(\log n),\ Worst = O(n)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A-->B;
              B-->C;
              C-->D;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise: Implement a Binary Tree

            In this exercise, you will implement a **binary tree data structure** from scratch.

            ### Your goals:

            1. Create a **Node class**
            2. Create a **BinaryTree class**
            3. Implement:
              - Insertion (level-order)
              - Inorder traversal
              - Preorder traversal
              - Postorder traversal

            ####Node = (value, left, right)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[10]-->B[5];
              A-->C[15];
              B-->D[3];
              B-->E[7];
            /mermaid

            ---

            ### Step-by-step Instructions

            **Step 1 — Create the Node class**
            - Each node should store:
              - value
              - left child
              - right child

            **Step 2 — Create the BinaryTree class**
            - Store the **root node**

            **Step 3 — Implement insertion**
            - Insert nodes using **level-order (BFS)**
            - Fill the tree from left to right

            **Step 4 — Implement traversals**
            - Inorder → Left, Root, Right
            - Preorder → Root, Left, Right
            - Postorder → Left, Right, Root

            ####Traversal = visiting\ all\ nodes####

            ---

            ### Expected Example

            If you insert:

            10, 5, 15, 3, 7

            You should get:

            - Inorder: 3, 5, 7, 10, 15
            - Preorder: 10, 5, 3, 7, 15
            - Postorder: 3, 7, 5, 15, 10

            ---

            spoiler

            ```
            from collections import deque

            class Node:
                def __init__(self, value):
                    self.value = value
                    self.left = None
                    self.right = None


            class BinaryTree:
                def __init__(self):
                    self.root = None

                def insert(self, value):
                    new_node = Node(value)

                    if not self.root:
                        self.root = new_node
                        return

                    queue = deque([self.root])

                    while queue:
                        current = queue.popleft()

                        if not current.left:
                            current.left = new_node
                            return
                        else:
                            queue.append(current.left)

                        if not current.right:
                            current.right = new_node
                            return
                        else:
                            queue.append(current.right)

                def inorder(self, node):
                    if not node:
                        return []
                    return self.inorder(node.left) + [node.value] + self.inorder(node.right)

                def preorder(self, node):
                    if not node:
                        return []
                    return [node.value] + self.preorder(node.left) + self.preorder(node.right)

                def postorder(self, node):
                    if not node:
                        return []
                    return self.postorder(node.left) + self.postorder(node.right) + [node.value]


            # Example usage
            tree = BinaryTree()
            values = [10, 5, 15, 3, 7]

            for v in values:
                tree.insert(v)

            print("Inorder:", tree.inorder(tree.root))
            print("Preorder:", tree.preorder(tree.root))
            print("Postorder:", tree.postorder(tree.root))
            ```
            /spoiler
            </script>
